✅ What is the purpose of the pages directory in Next.js?
The pages directory in Next.js is used to define routes and pages automatically using a file‑based routing system.
In simple terms:
👉 Every file inside pages/ becomes a route in your application.

🔹 Core Purpose of the pages Directory
1️⃣ Automatic Routing
Next.js automatically creates routes based on file names.

pages/
 ├── index.js      →  /
 ├── about.js      →  /about
 ├── blog/
 │    └── [id].js  →  /blog/123
✅ No need for React Router
✅ No manual route configuration

2️⃣ Page‑Level Rendering Control
Each file in pages/ represents a page, where you can define how the page is rendered:
	• SSR → getServerSideProps
	• SSG → getStaticProps
	• ISR → revalidation
	• CSR → normal React behavior

export async function getServerSideProps() {
  return { props: {} }
}

3️⃣ Special Files for App Behavior
File	Purpose
_app.js	Initialize pages, add global layout
_document.js	Customize HTML structure
404.js	Custom 404 page
500.js	Custom error page
_error.js	Custom error handling

4️⃣ Dynamic Routes Support
Using brackets ([]) allows dynamic routing:
pages/product/[id].js
➡️ /product/101
➡️ /product/202

5️⃣ API Routes (Backend Support)
The pages/api folder allows backend APIs inside the same app:
pages/api/login.js → /api/login
✅ No separate backend required
✅ Runs on the server only

🧠 Interview‑Ready Answer (30 Seconds)
	The pages directory in Next.js enables file‑based routing, where each file automatically becomes a route.
	It also allows page‑level data fetching using SSR, SSG, or ISR, and supports dynamic routes and API endpoints.
	This makes routing simpler and the application production‑ready by default.

⚠️ Important Note (Modern Next.js)
	• The pages directory is part of the Pages Router
	• Newer Next.js versions introduce the app directory (App Router)
	• Both can coexist, but you use one routing system at a time

✅ When to Use pages Directory
	• Existing or legacy Next.js projects
	• Simple routing requirements
	• Team familiarity with classic Next.js pattern

